\doxysubsection{详细描述}
Utilities for collecting timings. 

A trace represents the execution process of a single request in the system, span represents a logical operation unit with start time and execution duration in the system, and multiple spans form a trace.

Search for a substring in a string by Volnitsky\textquotesingle{}s algorithm \href{http://volnitsky.com/project/str_search/}{\texttt{ http\+://volnitsky.\+com/project/str\+\_\+search/}}

{\ttfamily haystack} and {\ttfamily needle} can contain zero bytes.

Algorithm\+:
\begin{DoxyItemize}
\item if the {\ttfamily needle} is too small or too large, or too small {\ttfamily haystack}, use std\+::search or memchr;
\item when initializing, fill in an open-\/addressing linear probing hash table of the form hash from the bigram of needle -\/\texorpdfstring{$>$}{>} the position of this bigram in needle + 1. (one is added only to distinguish zero offset from an empty cell)
\item the keys are not stored in the hash table, only the values are stored;
\item bigrams can be inserted several times if they occur in the needle several times;
\item when searching, take from haystack bigram, which should correspond to the last bigram of needle (comparing from the end);
\item look for it in the hash table, if found -\/ get the offset from the hash table and compare the string bytewise;
\item if it did not match, we check the next cell of the hash table from the collision resolution chain;
\item if not found, skip to haystack almost the size of the needle bytes;
\end{DoxyItemize}

Multi\+Volnitsky -\/ search for multiple substrings in a string\+:
\begin{DoxyItemize}
\item Add bigrams to hash table with string index. Then the usual Volnitsky search is used.
\item We are adding while searching, limiting the number of fallback searchers and the total number of added bigrams 
\end{DoxyItemize}

The flag means value\textquotesingle{}s length or null value\+: If value is nullptr, flag is 251 If value\textquotesingle{}s length \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} 251, flag is the value\textquotesingle{}s length If 251 \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<}= value\textquotesingle{}s length \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} 65536, flag is 252 and the next two bytes is length If 65536 \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<}= value\textquotesingle{}s length \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<} 16777216 , flag is 253 and the next three bytes is length If 16777216 \texorpdfstring{$<$}{<}= value\textquotesingle{}s length, flag is 254 and the next eighth bytes is length

the code example\+: mrb.\+push\+\_\+null(); mrb.\+push\+\_\+tinyint(5); mrb.\+push\+\_\+int(120); mrb.\+push\+\_\+string(\char`\"{}...\+my length is 65536...\char`\"{});

the protocol contents\+:

The type of \textquotesingle{}out\+\_\+val\textquotesingle{} depends on the value of \textquotesingle{}type\textquotesingle{}. Returns a value representing a point in time that is unaffected by daylight savings or manual adjustments to the system clock. This should not be assumed to be a Unix time. Typically the value corresponds to elapsed time since the system booted. See \mbox{\hyperlink{namespacedoris_a8c873b61acc89dfc24f33b7bc4757242}{Unix\+Millis()}} below if you need to send a time to a different host. 函数调用图\+:

Converts the input Unix time, \textquotesingle{}s\textquotesingle{}, specified in seconds since the Unix epoch, to a date-\/time string in the local time zone. The precision in the output date-\/time string is specified by the second argument, \textquotesingle{}p\textquotesingle{}. The returned string is of the format yyyy-\/\+MM-\/dd HH\+:mm\+:SS\mbox{[}.ms\mbox{[}us\mbox{[}ns\mbox{]}\mbox{]}. It\textquotesingle{}s worth noting that if the precision specified by \textquotesingle{}p\textquotesingle{} is higher than that of the input timestamp, the part corresponding to \textquotesingle{}p\textquotesingle{} in the fractional second part of the output will just be zero-\/padded. 函数调用图\+:
